      <lg type="edition">
<l>vaḷarat toṭiṉum vauvupu tirintu</l>
<l>viḷari yuṟutarun tīntoṭai niṉaiyāt</l>
<l>taḷaru neñcan talaii maṉaiyō</l>
<l>ḷuḷaruṅ kūnta ṉōkkik kaḷara</l>
<l>kaḷḷi nīḻaṟ kaṭavuḷ vāḻttip</l>
<l>pacipaṭu maruṅkulai kacipukai toḻāak</l>
<l>kāṇaleṉ kolleṉa viṉaviṉai varūum</l>
<l>pāṇa kēṇmati yāṇaratu nilaiyē</l>
<l>puravuttoṭut tuṇkuvai yāyiṉu miravuveḻun</l>
<l>tevvaṅ koḷkuvai yāyiṉu miraṇṭuṅ</l>
<l>kaiyuḷa pōluṅ kaṭitaṇ maiyavē</l>
<l>muṉṉūrp pūcaliṟ ṟōṉṟit taṉṉūr</l>
<l>neṭunirai taḻīiya mīḷi yāḷar</l>
<l>viṭukaṇai nīttan tuṭipuṇai yāka</l>
<l>veṉṟi tantu koṉṟukōḷ viṭuttu</l>
<l>vaiyakam pulampa vaḷaiiya pāmpiṉ</l>
<l>vaiyeyiṟ ṟuynta matiyiṉ maṟavar</l>
<l>kaiyakat tuynta kaṉṟuṭaip pallā</l>
<l>ṉiraiyoṭu vanta vuraiya ṉāki</l>
<l>yurikaḷai yarava māṉat tāṉē</l>
<l>yarituce lulakiṟ ceṉṟaṉa ṉuṭampē</l>
<l>kāṉac ciṟṟiyāṟ ṟaruṅkaraik kāluṟṟuk</l>
<l>kampamoṭu tuḷaṅkiya vilakkam pōla</l>
<l>vampoṭu tuḷaṅki yāṇṭoḻin taṉṟē</l>
<l>yuyaricai veṟuppat tōṉṟiya peyarē</l>
<l>maṭañcāṉ maññai yaṇimayir cūṭṭi</l>
<l>yiṭampiṟar koḷḷāc ciṟuvaḻip</l>
<l>paṭañcey pantark kaṉmicai yatuvē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Thinking of the sweet strings tuned in Viḷari (2)</l>
<l>after touching [them] so that [the note?] grows, gripping [and] swerving, (1)</l>
<l>offering [your] weary heart, looking at (3a-c)</l>
<l>the ruffled tresses of the lady of the house, praising</l>
<l>the deity in the shade of the salt-ground[-grown] spurge, (3d-5)</l>
<l>you with a waist that has experienced hunger, compassionate, folding [your] hands, (6)</l>
<l>o bard who comes asking “do I not see [him]?”, (7-8a)</l>
<l>listen [what is] the stated of [our] prosperity: (8b-d)</l>
<l>Whether you eat, taking on a boon [or] whether you rise for begging (9)</l>
<l>[and] accept misery, just two (10)</l>
<l>actions exist, it seems, that are quickly at hand. (11)</l>
<l>	Being one of [his] word who, (19cd)</l>
<l>after appearing in the skirmish at the village in front, bringing victory,</l>
<l>with the Tuṭi drum as a support, in the flood of arrows</l>
<l>sent out by the commanding men who had enveloped the large herd</l>
<l>of his village, killing, setting free the catch (~ the cows stolen by those men), (12-15)</l>
<l>came [back] with the herds (19ab)</l>
<l>of many calf-possessing cows that had escaped from the hands (18)</l>
<l>of bold men like the moon that escapes from the sharp teeth (17)</l>
<l>of the snake that had encircled [it] so that the world lamented, (16)</l>
<l>he himself, like the snake that sheds [its] skin, (20)</l>
<l>has gone to the world difficult to go to. [His] body, (21)</l>
<l>catching [his] foot on the difficult shore of the little forest river, (22)</l>
<l>like the target that sways with [its] pole, (23)</l>
<l>swaying with arrows it has remained behind there. (24)</l>
<l>[His] name that appeared much in high fame, (25)</l>
<l>wearing as a decoration the feathers of a youthful peacock (26) </l>
<l>it is [now] on a stone, with a shade made of cloth, (28)</l>
<l>on the little way not taken by strangers to [this] place. (27)</l>
</lg>
